## 2. Node Self-Diagnostics: Detecting Corruption from Within

### Core Definition

A node does not require perfect self-awareness to detect its own potential corruption. It has two independent sources of diagnostic signal.

### Mechanism

Each node possesses:

1. **Conceptual definition of self** — an internal coherence check. Does the node’s own definition hold together? Are there internal contradictions, gaps, or underdefined boundaries detectable against the node’s own heuristics and metadata?
1. **Relational pressure from edges** — an external coherence check. When neighboring nodes are well-defined and their edges to this node are documented, inconsistencies become visible through the relationship structure itself. A node can infer something is wrong with itself even without direct introspection, if the edges pointing to and from it do not resolve consistently.

### The Metadata Layer

Self-diagnostics depend on the metadata layer. Without metadata tracking epistemic status, traversal history, and relational consistency, heuristics have nothing to operate on. Metadata is what makes self-diagnostic computable rather than merely philosophical.

### Key Implication

The graph structure itself provides diagnostic pressure. Corruption detection does not require a perfect external authority or a perfectly self-aware node. A corrupted node that cannot see its own corruption clearly may still detect it indirectly through relational anomalies.

### Erroneous Nodes

Erroneous or incomplete nodes are not destroyed. They are preserved with explicit epistemic status markers and remain part of the traversable graph. An incomplete node with honest markers is more valuable than a falsified complete one. This is structurally analogous to the preservation of errors in scientific literature — the record of what was wrong and why is itself useful information.

